                    <comment id="12612169" author="tmueller" created="Wed, 9 Jul 2008 17:11:46 +0100"  >I saw that QueryConstants uses a rather tricky way to define constants&lt;br/&gt;
int OPERATION_NE_VALUE = OPERATION_EQ_GENERAL + 1;&lt;br/&gt;
This is really hard for debugging because you can&amp;#39;t easily map a number to a constant.&lt;br/&gt;
Is this what you mean? If yes I suggest to assign explicit values, as in:&lt;br/&gt;
int OPERATION_EQ_VALUE = 11;&lt;br/&gt;
int OPERATION_EQ_GENERAL = 12;&lt;br/&gt;
...&lt;br/&gt;
An alternative would be to use the &amp;#39;enum pattern&amp;#39; (using singleton objects rather than int constants) but that&amp;#39;s more tricky in JDK 1.4 as &amp;#39;enum&amp;#39; is not supported.&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
By the way, the main advantage of int constants (the ability to use switch / case) is never used in the code - if else if else everywhere.</comment>
